", "prob": 0.8805267214775085, "span": {"begin": 732, "end": 743}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:983"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Cdk-1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9977294206619263, "span": {"begin": 821, "end": 826}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1019"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Cdk-4", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9984069466590881, "span": {"begin": 828, "end": 833}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:595"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Cyclin D1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9987240433692932, "span": {"begin": 835, "end": 844}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5111"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Pcna", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9964107871055603, "span": {"begin": 859, "end": 863}}], "text": "Growth factors and other cytokines&nbsp;secreted from Kupffer cells following PPAR&alpha; activation include&nbsp;tumor necrosis factor &alpha; (TNF&alpha;), interleukin-1&alpha; (IL-1&alpha;), and interleukin-1&beta; (IL-1&beta;). Although TNF&alpha; levels increase following PPAR&alpha; activation, proliferation was observed in wild type, TNF&alpha;-null, and&nbsp;TNF&alpha; receptor-null mice, suggesting that multiple cytokines stimulate cell proliferation (Maeda et al. 2005). PPAR&alpha; activation reduces the level of miRNA let-7c in liver. In turn, let-7c normally down-regulates c-Myc expression and thus,&nbsp;PPAR&alpha; activation increases c-Myc expression that increase cell proliferation (Shah et al. 2007).&nbsp;PPAR&alpha; activation increases levels of other cell cycle proteins&nbsp;including&nbsp;Cdk-1, Cdk-4, Cyclin D1&nbsp;and&nbsp;Pcna&nbsp;(Currie et al. 2005; Woods et al. 2007).  &nbsp;", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:36:09 +0000 2026"}